The Kenai Peninsula ([Dena'ina](/Dena%CA%BCina_language): *Yaghenen*) is a substantial [peninsula](/Peninsula) that thrusts itself from the coastline of [Southcentral Alaska](/Southcentral_Alaska), as if trying to escape the mainland. The name Kenai ([/ˈkiːnaɪ/](/Help:IPA/English), KEE-ny), a name now slapped on everything from fjords to fish, is a linguistic hand-me-down, derived from "Kenaitze" or "Kenaitze Indian Tribe." This was the name given to the Native Athabascan Alaskan people, the Kahtnuht’ana Dena’ina, which translates to "People along the [Kahtnu (Kenai River)](/Kenai_River)," who had the sense to inhabit the area long before anyone else showed up to name it. They called the Kenai Peninsula *Yaghanen*, or "the good land." An optimistic assessment, but they didn't have to deal with tourists.

### Geography

If you're looking for a landmark to orient your hopelessly lost self, Tern Lake sits at the junction of the two main roads that grant access to this place. It's a geographical crossroads, which is a polite way of saying it's where you decide which direction you're going to get stuck in.

The peninsula extends roughly 150 miles (240 km) southwest, peeling away from the [Chugach Mountains](/Chugach_Mountains), which loom south of [Anchorage](/Anchorage,_Alaska). It’s a land defined by its borders of water. To the west, the frigid, silt-heavy waters of [Cook Inlet](/Cook_Inlet) create a formidable barrier. To the east, the deeper, darker expanse of [Prince William Sound](/Prince_William_Sound) carves out its territory. The vast majority of this landmass falls under the jurisdiction of the [Kenai Peninsula Borough](/Kenai_Peninsula_Borough,_Alaska), a political boundary drawn over a landscape that couldn't care less. Before the era of [Russian America](/Russian_America) brought maps and manifest destiny, [Athabaskan](/Athabaskan) and [Alutiiq](/Alutiiq) peoples thrived here for millennia, leaving a history far deeper than any colonial footnote.

A formidable spine of [glacier](/Glacier)-carved peaks, the [Kenai Mountains](/Kenai_Mountains), runs the length of the peninsula's southeast coast, a jagged wall against the [Gulf of Alaska](/Gulf of Alaska). A significant portion of this unforgiving range is protected, or perhaps imprisoned, within [Kenai Fjords National Park](/Kenai_Fjords_National_Park). In stark contrast, the northwest coast, which faces the Cook Inlet, is a flatter, more subdued landscape, pockmarked by countless small lakes. Deeper within the peninsula's interior, several larger bodies of water assert their presence, including the formidable [Skilak Lake](/Skilak_Lake) and the even more imposing [Tustumena Lake](/Tustumena_Lake).

Its rivers are its lifelines. The most famous, the [Kenai River](/Kenai_River), is a pilgrimage site for those obsessed with wrestling [king salmon](/King_salmon) from its glacial, turquoise waters. It’s fed by tributaries like the [Russian River](/Russian_River_(Alaska)), another theater for the annual combat between fish and fisher. Other significant waterways include the [Kasilof River](/Kasilof_River) and the [Anchor River](/Anchor_River). Tucked into the peninsula's southwest corner is [Kachemak Bay](/Kachemak_Bay), a dramatic inlet branching off the greater [Cook Inlet](/Cook_Inlet). Much of its stunning, rugged coastline is designated as [Kachemak Bay State Park](/Kachemak_Bay_State_Park).

This is also a land of ice. It is the dominion of both the [Sargent Icefield](/Sargent_Icefield) and the massive [Harding Icefield](/Harding_Icefield), sprawling seas of ancient ice from which numerous glaciers are born. These rivers of ice, including the notable [Tustumena Glacier](/Tustumena_Glacier), the accessible [Exit Glacier](/Exit_Glacier), and the tidewater [McCarty Glacier](/McCarty_Glacier), continue to sculpt the landscape with glacial indifference.

### Towns and cities

Despite its rugged nature, the peninsula hosts several of Southcentral Alaska's more significant settlements. These dots of civilization cling to the coastlines and riverbanks. You'll find [Seward](/Seward,_Alaska) on the Gulf of Alaska, the gateway to the fjords and the open ocean. Along the Cook Inlet and the banks of the Kenai River are the pragmatic hubs of [Soldotna](/Soldotna,_Alaska), [Kenai](/Kenai,_Alaska), and [Sterling](/Sterling,_Alaska), with [Cooper Landing](/Cooper_Landing,_Alaska) nestled in the mountains. At the literal end of the road, perched on the edge of Kachemak Bay, is [Homer](/Homer,_Alaska). These are accompanied by a constellation of smaller villages and settlements, each with its own brand of determined survival.

### Transportation

Getting around is less a matter of convenience and more a matter of choosing your challenge. The ferry *Tustumena* is a common sight as it approaches Homer, a vital link in a chain of transport.

[Homer](/Homer,_Alaska) holds the distinct, and perhaps lonely, honor of being the terminus of the paved highway system of [North America](/North_America). Go any further by car, and you're driving into the ocean. The nearby community of [Anchor Point](/Anchor_Point,_Alaska) claims the title of the most westerly point on the contiguous highway system, a fine point of trivia for those who appreciate endings. The port city of [Seward](/Seward,_Alaska) serves as the southern terminus of the [Alaska Railroad](/Alaska_Railroad), another lifeline of steel connecting the peninsula to the north.

The primary asphalt arteries are the [Seward Highway](/Seward_Highway), which provides the essential link between Seward and [Anchorage](/Anchorage,_Alaska), and the [Sterling Highway](/Sterling_Highway), which branches off to connect the peninsula's larger population centers. For more localized travel, the [Kenai Spur Highway](/Kenai_Spur_Highway) connects the cluster of communities including Soldotna, Kenai, and Nikiski, eventually reaching [Captain Cook State Recreation Area](/Captain_Cook_State_Recreation_Area).

For those who prefer to travel above the fray, commercial airports with regular service to Anchorage are located in [Kenai](/Kenai_Airport) and [Homer](/Homer_Airport). A network of smaller airfields serves more local needs in [Soldotna](/Soldotna_Airport), [Seward](/Seward_Airport), and [Seldovia](/Seldovia_Airport).

For those who travel by sea, the [Alaska Marine Highway](/Alaska_Marine_Highway) provides ferry service to the ports of Homer and [Seldovia](/Seldovia). Seward, meanwhile, has established itself as a major port of call for the colossal cruise ships that patrol these waters during the summer months.

### Natural resources and economy

Beneath the surface, the peninsula holds deposits of [natural gas](/Natural_gas), [petroleum](/Petroleum), and [coal](/Coal)—the usual geologic lottery winnings. Its waters, however, are its most visible and vital resource, supporting abundant commercial and personal-use fisheries that are the lifeblood of many communities.

[Tourism](/Tourism) has become a dominant industry, with fleets of outfitting and guiding services catering to eager hunters and fishers. In a stroke of marketing genius, or perhaps irony, the Kenai Peninsula is widely known as "Alaska's Playground." It's a playground where the swings hang over fjords and the sandbox is a two-million-acre wilderness. Nearly two million acres of the peninsula are designated as the [Kenai National Wildlife Refuge](/Kenai_National_Wildlife_Refuge), a sprawling sanctuary established in a grand attempt to keep the playground from being completely trampled.

